Show me a woman who is incredibly beautiful. What does her beauty serve as, other than a reminder of who was that beautiful woman? Goodbye, you can't teach me to forget. BENVOLIO. I'll learn that lesson, or else die trying. [_They exit._]

SCENE II. A Street. Enter Capulet, Paris and Servant. CAPULET. But Montague is just as responsible as I am, we're both liable to the same penalty. It's not hard, I think, for men as old as we are to keep the peace. PARIS. Both of you are honorable men, it's a shame you've been at odds for so long. But now, my lord, what do you think of my proposal? CAPULET. I'm just repeating what I've said before. My daughter is still a child, she hasn't even turned fourteen yet. Let's wait two more years before we consider her ready for marriage. PARIS. There are younger girls who are happily married. CAPULET. And those who marry too early often end up unhappy. She is my only hope, the rest are gone. But try to win her over, gentle Paris, win her heart. My approval is only part of it; she also has to agree. Tonight, I'm hosting a traditional feast, and I've invited many guests, including you. At my humble home tonight, you'll see beauties that outshine the stars. You'll feel the same joy that young men feel when spring follows winter. You'll experience such delight among the young women at my house. See them all, and choose the one you like the most. Among many, my daughter may stand out, even if she's not the most beautiful. Come, go with me. Go, servant, find the people on this list [_gives a paper_] and tell them they're welcome to stay at my house as long as they like. [_Capulet and Paris exit._]

SERVANT. Find the people whose names are written here! It's like a shoemaker trying to fish, or a tailor trying to paint. I'm supposed to find these people, but I can't read the names. I need to find someone who can read. Just in time! Enter Benvolio and Romeo. BENVOLIO. Listen, one fire can put out another, one pain can lessen another. If you're dizzy, turn around; it might help. If you're desperate, another's desperation might cure you. Get a new crush, and you'll forget the old one. ROMEO. Your plantain leaf is excellent for that. BENVOLIO. For what, may I ask? ROMEO. For your broken shin. BENVOLIO. Why, Romeo, are you crazy? ROMEO. Not crazy, but more trapped than a madman. Locked up, starved, whipped and tormented. Hello, good man. SERVANT. Hello. Sir, can you read? ROMEO. Yes, my own misfortune in my misery. SERVANT. Maybe you learned it without a book. But can you read anything you see? ROMEO. Yes, if I know the letters and the language. SERVANT. You're honest, have a good day! ROMEO. Wait, I can read. [_He reads the letter._]

_Signior Martino and his wife and daughters;
County Anselmo and his beautiful sisters;
The lady widow of Utruvio;
Signior Placentio and his lovely nieces;
Mercutio and his brother Valentine;
My uncle Capulet, his wife, and daughters;
My beautiful niece Rosaline and Livia;
Signior Valentio and his cousin Tybalt;
Lucio and the lively Helena._

Quite a gathering. [_Gives back the paper_] Where are they going? SERVANT. Up. ROMEO. To dinner? SERVANT. To our house. ROMEO. Whose house? SERVANT. My master's. ROMEO. I should have asked you that before. SERVANT. Now I'll tell you without you asking. My master is the wealthy Capulet, and if you're not a Montague, please come and have a glass of wine. Have a good day. [_Exit._]

BENVOLIO. At this same traditional feast of Capulet's, the beautiful Rosaline you love so much will be there, along with all the other beauties of Verona. Go there and compare her with the others, and I'll make you see your swan as a crow. ROMEO. 

